player.seasonOutlook: Singer, a first-round pick by the Royals back in 2018, was traded to the Reds this past November in exchange for Jonathan India and Joey Wiemer. The move from Kansas City to Cincinnati comes with a park downgrade, although it's not as significant as one might suspect, at least not in terms of overall run scoring. Great American Ball Park plays more favorably for power hitting, but Singer's heavy sinker approach should help mitigate that factor, at least in theory. He upped his strikeout rate last season and has shown decent swing-and-miss ability with his breaking pitches, though Singer's strikeout rate has typically hovered around league average. While he should be drafted as a streamer in 2025, Singer could emerge as a more regular option for fantasy managers if new skipper Terry Francona can push the right buttons and protect his leads.

Following his return from July 2023 elbow surgery -- an internal brace procedure, after he had twice previously had Tommy John surgery -- Rasmussen was eased back into action by the Rays, largely as a reliever. He acclimated himself well to the switch, reflecting spikes in his average fastball velocity and strikeout rate, which offers promise heading into 2025. Rasmussen should return to the Rays rotation to begin the year, but keep in mind that their conservative approach to pitching workloads means the right-hander might be looking at closer to a 120- than a 160-inning workload. Still, he has the skills to be an every-start fantasy option while available if his stuff looks as good in March as it did last September.

Boyd fared remarkably well in his return from June 2023 Tommy John surgery across eight late-season starts and an additional three during the postseason, posting a 2.28 ERA and a 28.2% strikeout rate. Most importantly, both his slider and changeup appeared to have similar life to their pre-surgery models, which was apparently enough for the Cubs to commit $29 million to him across the next two seasons. Boyd's career has reflected much streakiness in terms of his control, and his injury history is a concern. However, so long as he's valued as more of a back-of-your-staff mixed-league type, he's well worth taking a chance.

Sale's Comeback Player of the Year campaign earned him his first career Cy Young Award in 2024, fueled by what were his best single-year strikeout, whiff and hard-hit rates allowed as well as his best average fastball velocity since before his March 2020 Tommy John surgery. Best yet, he only seemed to improve as the season progressed, posting a 1.88 ERA and a 33.2% strikeout rate across his final 16 starts, signaling his ability to maintain an elite level of performance despite his 35 years of age. Back issues prematurely ended Sale's campaign. That's an injury which bears watching throughout spring training, but if he's in the clear on that front, he's plenty capable of delivering top-10 fantasy SP numbers again.

The centerpiece of the 2023-24 offseason's Juan Soto trade, King proved every bit as capable a starting pitcher across 30 starts for the Padres last season as he was over an eight-start stint for the Yankees to conclude 2023. In fact, King was one of only four pitchers to strike out at least 200 batters with a sub-3.00 ERA, joining both Cy Young Award winners (Chris Sale, Tarik Skubal) and Zack Wheeler. He only strengthened his underlying numbers over the season's second half, getting a whiff nearly one-third of the time hitters swung at any of his pitches. It sets up the right-hander well for a similarly productive 2025, albeit with some risk of ERA regression, as his Statcast xERA should be nearly three-quarters of a run higher. Still, that's a top-20 capable fantasy starter regardless of format.

Severino and the rest of the Athletics will be playing their home games at Sutter Health Park in West Sacramento this season, in a park that will also remain home to the Triple-A Sacramento River Cats of the Pacific Coast League. The move does not bode well for the pitching staff, at least not on paper, but this is what Severino signed up for when he inked a three-year deal in December. The right-hander rebounded with the Mets in 2024, clearing 30 starts for the first time since 2018 as one of nine pitchers in the National League to exceed 180 innings last season. Severino still throws hard for a starting pitcher, but his strikeout rate has fallen precipitously in recent years, from above 35 percent at his peak to just 21.1 percent last season. The team context and questionable upside will drive many away.

Lopez is a legitimate frontline starter in Major League Baseball, if not quite a fantasy ace. The right-hander has been dependable, taking the ball 32 times and reaching 180 innings each of the past three seasons -- the last two with Minnesota. Always stingy with walks, Lopez shaved his walk rate to a career-low 5.3 percent last season, which helped him keep his WHIP below 1.20 for the fifth consecutive campaign. He has five different pitches, all of which can generate whiffs, though his changeup was not as effective in 2024. Regardless, Lopez found his groove in the second half, pitching to a 2.77 ERA in 81.1 innings after the break. While Lopez may not look like a particularly flashy upside pick, he misses enough bats and could easily return to All-Star status. He has often underperformed his estimators, though it's always possible he could have a year where the results beat the peripherals.

Sanchez impressed by going 11-9 with a 3.32 ERA and 1.24 WHIP across 181.2 innings last season, his first as a full-time member of the Philadelphia rotation. The lefty's game is built around the sinking fastball which was the main driver in a 57.4 percent groundball rate last season, third highest among qualified starters. In turn, he allowed just 11 homers for the third-best HR/9 among that group. Sanchez can also pull the string on a changeup and spin a breaking ball, though the package has not included many strikeouts to date. It's possible that Sanchez, still just 28 years old, could unlock another level with the strikeouts, but that should not be expected since there is little reason to mess with a formula that has been largely successful. The K rate as it stands now caps his upside, but Sanchez looks like a viable pick to fill out any fantasy rotation in 2025.

Eovaldi went a long way in shedding the fragility label by throwing his second-highest innings total last season. He will miss a start from time to time, as he has but twice made 30 starts, but when he is out there, he works deep into games thanks to his ability to throw four different pitches to lefties and five to righties. The repertoire is a bit susceptible to the long ball, but Eovaldi's stinginess with walks offsets the damage from those homers. He is one of just six pitchers to have posted an ERA of 4.00 and a WHIP below 1.25 while pitching at least 100 innings in each of the past four seasons, joining the likes of Framber Valdez, Corbin Burnes, Kevin Gausman, Logan Webb and Zack Wheeler. That's good company to keep.

How you regard Burnes might come down to these conflicting thoughts: Is his precipitous, four-year pattern of declining strikeout rates worrisome, or does the Diamondbacks' six-year, $210 million commitment to the right-hander strengthen confidence in his skills? The answer might lie somewhere in between. Burnes and Logan Webb are the only pitchers with at least 95 starts, 60 quality starts and 590 IP over the past three seasons. That durailbity, combined with his repertoire tweaks -- he's increasingly going for minimizing hard contact rather than for swings and misses -- diminish the instinct to panic about possible skills erosion. Burnes might no longer be a Cy Young favorite, but he looks the part of dependable top-10 fantasy starting pitcher.

Irvin's 33 starts tied for most in the majors last season, as he pitched a career-high 187.2 innings. His 4.41 ERA was a tad high according to a 4.03 xFIP and 4.21 SIERA. With a low 20.3 percent strikeout rate, Irvin is more susceptible to variance, which is amplified by a high home run rate. Irvin improved his strikeout and walk rates last season and is just 28 years old, so he could continue to improve. The Nationals are also developing something of a reputation for developing pitching. The safe play is paying for the floor and deploying Irvin sagely, avoiding power-laden lineups.
